The paper focuses on sensorimotor learning in a modular co-evolution strategy, which involves the coordination of multiple agents to dynamically self-assemble into composite bodies. This suggests a strong emphasis on robotics (cs.RO) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the performance of these agents in simulated environments, which suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper mentions the use of policies to control the morphology of the agents, which suggests a focus on neural networks (cs.NE).
